  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Hervey Eliphaz Weston was quite sick on Thanksgiving day. He has been to West Rock and Judges&apos; Cave. He describes the cave in which (William) Goffey and (Edward) Whalley lived for a number of years. He refers to a book about them by the &quot;old president [Ezra] Stiles.&quot; Hervey E. Weston says that &quot;poor Fletcher is sick yet,&quot; and has inquired &quot;how soon is your sister coming.&quot; There was a commotion in the college yard by five or six fellows, who were &quot;acting more like mad than anything else,&quot; the cause being two southerners &quot;with their hands full of Abolition tracts and newspapers and a number of others of the same stamp cursing and swearing&quot; and threatening to tar and feather Pierce, &quot;the fellow who distributed them.&quot; A meeting called by &quot;the Bully Bennet&quot; came to nothing. The southerners were obliged to withdraw their resolutions. They tried to hiss at a fellow who spoke an abolition piece in the chapel, but could not. Hervey E. Weston is geting on well in his lessons.</subfield>
